#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:-1
msgid ""
"A guide to packaging Perl modules with Spack, covering when to add a package "
"and build system integration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:13
msgid "Perl"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:15
msgid ""
"Much like Octave, Perl has its own language-specific build system. This "
"documentation includes information on when **not** to add a Spack package "
"for a Perl module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:22
msgid "Suitable Modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:24
msgid ""
"In general, modules that are part of the standard Perl installation should "
"not be added to Spack. A possible exception is if the module was not part of "
"the standard installation for earlier versions of ``perl`` that are still "
"listed in the package, which you can check by running ``spack info perl``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:27
msgid ""
"How do you know if the module is in the standard Perl installation? You "
"check if it is included in the ``CORE`` by entering the following on the "
"command line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:30
msgid "$ corelist <perl-module>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:34
msgid "where <perl-module> is case sensitive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:36
msgid ""
"Examples of outputs for modules that are and are not in the ``CORE`` using "
"perl v5.42.0 are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:38
msgid ""
"$ corelist Carp\n"
"\n"
"Data for 2025-07-02\n"
"Carp was first released with perl 5\n"
"\n"
"$ corelist XML::Writer\n"
"\n"
"Data for 2025-07-02\n"
"XML::Writer was not in CORE (or so I think)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:52
msgid "Phases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:54
msgid ""
"The ``PerlBuilder`` and ``PerlPackage`` base classes come with three phases "
"that can be overridden:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:56
msgid "``configure`` - configure the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:57
msgid "``build`` - build the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:58
msgid "``install`` - install the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:60
msgid "Perl packages have two common modules used for module installation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:63
msgid "``ExtUtils::MakeMaker``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:65
msgid ""
"The ``ExtUtils::MakeMaker`` module is just what it sounds like, a module "
"designed to generate Makefiles. It can be identified by the presence of a "
"``Makefile.PL`` file, and has the following installation steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:68
msgid ""
"$ perl Makefile.PL INSTALL_BASE=/path/to/installation/prefix\n"
"$ make\n"
"$ make test  # optional\n"
"$ make install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:77
msgid "``Module::Build``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:79
msgid ""
"The ``Module::Build`` module is a pure-Perl build system, and can be "
"identified by the presence of a ``Build.PL`` file. It has the following "
"installation steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:82
msgid ""
"$ perl Build.PL --install_base /path/to/installation/prefix\n"
"$ ./Build\n"
"$ ./Build test  # optional\n"
"$ ./Build install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:90
msgid ""
"If both ``Makefile.PL`` and ``Build.PL`` files exist in the package, Spack "
"will use ``Makefile.PL`` by default. If your package uses a different "
"module, ``PerlPackage`` will need to be extended to support it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:93
msgid ""
"``PerlPackage`` automatically detects which build steps to use, so there "
"shouldn't be much work on the package developer's side to get things working."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:96
msgid "Finding Perl packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:98
msgid ""
"Most Perl modules are hosted on CPAN, the Comprehensive Perl Archive "
"Network. If you need to find a package for ``XML::Parser``, for example, you "
"should search for \"CPAN XML::Parser\". Just make sure that the module is "
"not included in the ``CORE`` (see :ref:`suitable_perl_modules`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:102
msgid ""
"Some CPAN pages are versioned. Check for a link to the \"Latest Release\" to "
"make sure you have the latest version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:107
msgid "Package name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:109
msgid ""
"When you use ``spack create`` to create a new Perl package, Spack will "
"automatically prepend ``perl-`` to the front of the package name. This helps "
"to keep Perl modules separate from other packages. The same naming scheme is "
"used for other language extensions, like Python and R. See :ref:`creating-"
"and-editing-packages` for more information on the command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:115
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:117
msgid ""
"Most CPAN pages have a short description under \"NAME\" and a longer "
"description under \"DESCRIPTION\". Use whichever you think is more useful "
"while still being succinct."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:121
msgid "Homepage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:123
msgid ""
"In the top-right corner of the CPAN page, you'll find a \"permalink\" for "
"the package. This should be used instead of the current URL, as it doesn't "
"contain the version number and will always link to the latest release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:127
msgid "URL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:129
msgid ""
"If you haven't found it already, the download URL is on the right side of "
"the page below the permalink. Search for \"Download\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:133
msgid "Build system dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:135
msgid ""
"Every ``PerlPackage`` obviously depends on Perl at build and run-time, so "
"``PerlPackage`` contains:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:137
msgid "extends(\"perl\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:142
msgid ""
"If your package requires a specific version of Perl, you should specify this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:144
msgid ""
"Although newer versions of Perl include ``ExtUtils::MakeMaker`` and "
"``Module::Build`` as \"core\" modules, you may want to add dependencies on "
"``perl-extutils-makemaker`` and ``perl-module-build`` anyway. Many people "
"add Perl as an external package, and we want the build to work properly. If "
"your package uses ``Makefile.PL`` to build, add:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:148
msgid "depends_on(\"perl-extutils-makemaker\", type=\"build\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:153
msgid "If your package uses ``Build.PL`` to build, add:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:155
msgid "depends_on(\"perl-module-build\", type=\"build\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:161
msgid "Perl dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:163
msgid ""
"Below the download URL, you will find a \"Dependencies\" link, which takes "
"you to a page listing all of the dependencies of the package. Packages "
"listed as \"Core module\" don't need to be added as dependencies, but all "
"direct dependencies should be added. Don't add dependencies of dependencies. "
"These should be added as dependencies to the dependency, not to your package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:169
msgid "Passing arguments to configure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:171
msgid ""
"Packages that have non-Perl dependencies often use command-line variables to "
"specify their installation directory. You can pass arguments to ``Makefile."
"PL`` or ``Build.PL`` by overriding ``configure_args`` like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:174
msgid ""
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    expat = self.spec[\"expat\"].prefix\n"
"\n"
"    return [\n"
"        \"EXPATLIBPATH={0}\".format(expat.lib),\n"
"        \"EXPATINCPATH={0}\".format(expat.include),\n"
"    ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:186
msgid "Testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:188
msgid ""
"``PerlPackage`` provides a simple stand-alone test of the successfully "
"installed package to confirm that installed Perl module(s) can be used. "
"These tests can be performed any time after the installation using ``spack -"
"v test run``. (For more information on the command, see :ref:`cmd-spack-test-"
"run`.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:192
msgid ""
"The base class automatically detects Perl modules based on the presence of "
"``*.pm`` files under the package's library directory. For example, the files "
"under ``perl-bignum``'s Perl library are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:195
msgid ""
"$ find . -name \"*.pm\"\n"
"./bigfloat.pm\n"
"./bigrat.pm\n"
"./Math/BigFloat/Trace.pm\n"
"./Math/BigInt/Trace.pm\n"
"./Math/BigRat/Trace.pm\n"
"./bigint.pm\n"
"./bignum.pm"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:207
msgid ""
"which results in the package having the ``use_modules`` property containing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:209
msgid ""
"use_modules = [\n"
"    \"bigfloat\",\n"
"    \"bigrat\",\n"
"    \"Math::BigFloat::Trace\",\n"
"    \"Math::BigInt::Trace\",\n"
"    \"Math::BigRat::Trace\",\n"
"    \"bigint\",\n"
"    \"bignum\",\n"
"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:223
msgid "This list can often be used to catch missing dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:225
msgid ""
"If the list is somehow wrong, you can provide the names of the modules "
"yourself by overriding ``use_modules`` like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:227
msgid "use_modules = [\"bigfloat\", \"bigrat\", \"bigint\", \"bignum\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:231
msgid ""
"If you only want a subset of the automatically detected modules to be "
"tested, you could instead define the ``skip_modules`` property on the "
"package. So, instead of overriding ``use_modules`` as shown above, you could "
"define the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:234
msgid ""
"skip_modules = [\n"
"    \"Math::BigFloat::Trace\",\n"
"    \"Math::BigInt::Trace\",\n"
"    \"Math::BigRat::Trace\",\n"
"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:242
msgid "for the same use tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:245
msgid "Alternatives to Spack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:247
msgid ""
"If you need to maintain a stack of Perl modules for a user and don't want to "
"add all of them to Spack, a good alternative is ``cpanm``. If Perl is "
"already installed on your system, it should come with a ``cpan`` executable. "
"To install ``cpanm``, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:251
msgid "$ cpan App::cpanminus"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:256
msgid "Now, you can install any Perl module you want by running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:258
msgid "$ cpanm Module::Name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:263
msgid ""
"Obviously, these commands can only be run if you have root privileges. "
"Furthermore, ``cpanm`` is not capable of installing non-Perl dependencies. "
"If you need to install to your home directory or need to install a module "
"with non-Perl dependencies, Spack is a better option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:268
msgid "External documentation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:270
msgid ""
"You can find more information on installing Perl modules from source at: "
"http://www.perlmonks.org/?node_id=128077"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/perlpackage.rst:272
msgid ""
"More generic Perl module installation instructions can be found at: http://"
"www.cpan.org/modules/INSTALL.html"
msgstr ""
